			<div class="site-column site-column-content"><div class="site-column-wrapper clearfix"><!-- .site-column .site-column-1 .site-column-aside --><h1 class="page-title">Soft Cyber Laws Make Port Facilities Soft Cyber Targets</h1><p class="entry-meta"><span class="post-meta-wrapper"><span class="post-meta-span post-meta-span-time">on <time datetime="2021-05-06" pubdate>May 6, 2021</time></span></span><!-- .post-meta-wrapper --></p><!-- .entry-meta --><div class="entry-content"><p><em>By CDR Michael C. Petta</em></p>
<p>There is widespread recognition that cybersecurity vulnerabilities make the maritime transportation system a soft target. For example, about 10 years ago, a European Union study found “inadequate preparedness regarding cyber risks” in the maritime sector. In 2013, a U.S. Presidential Executive Order announced that cyber threats continue to grow as one of the most serious security challenges for critical infrastructure, such as port facilities. A few years later, an International Maritime Organization (IMO) resolution acknowledged the “urgent need” to address maritime cyber threats.</p>
<figure id="attachment_41140" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-41140" style="width: 300px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" class="size-medium wp-image-41140" src="http://www.marsecreview.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/cyber-security-cybersecurity-device-60504-300x200.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="200" srcset="http://www.marsecreview.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/cyber-security-cybersecurity-device-60504-300x200.jpg 300w, http://www.marsecreview.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/cyber-security-cybersecurity-device-60504-1024x683.jpg 1024w, http://www.marsecreview.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/cyber-security-cybersecurity-device-60504-768x512.jpg 768w, http://www.marsecreview.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/cyber-security-cybersecurity-device-60504-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, http://www.marsecreview.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/cyber-security-cybersecurity-device-60504-2048x1365.jpg 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-41140" class="wp-caption-text">Cyber security, via Pexels</figcaption></figure>
<p>Just a few days after that IMO resolution, Maersk, the global shipping company, suffered a major cyberattack, leading its chairman to admit in an interview that the maritime industry had been naïve with cybersecurity and needs “radical improvement.”</p>
<p>To read the entire article, <a href="https://www.maritime-executive.com/editorials/soft-cyber-laws-make-port-facilities-soft-cyber-targets" target="_blank" rel="noopener">please click here.</a></p>
<p>Source: maritime-executive.com</p>
